---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
	title='FAQ: Guitar Lessons in Suwanee, GA | Jonathan Zalzman'
	description='Frequently asked questions about guitar, bass, and ukulele lessons with Jonathan Zalzman in Suwanee, GA. Pricing, scheduling, what to expect, and more.'
	nav='faq'
>
<!-- ===================== PAGE HERO ===================== -->
<section class="page-hero">
  <div class="page-hero-inner">
    <div class="crumbs">
      <a href="/">Home</a>
      <span class="sep">/</span>
      <span>FAQ</span>
    </div>
    <div class="page-num"><span class="ix">04</span> Common Questions</div>
    <h1>Everything <em>You're</em><br>About to <span class="accent">Ask Me.</span></h1>
    <p class="page-lede">Six categories. Thirty-ish questions. <b>If yours isn't here</b>, just email or call, I answer either fast.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ===================== FAQ ===================== -->
<section class="page-section">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="faq-cat">
      <div class="faq-cat-head">
        <span class="cat-num">// 01</span>
        <h2>Getting Started</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">My kid has never touched a guitar. Are they too young or too new? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Lessons are open to anyone age 6 and up. Brand-new students get a foundation track that introduces holding the instrument, basic chords, and reading enough to play actual songs they care about within the first few weeks. There's no prerequisite beyond showing up.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">I haven't played in 20 years. Can I still take lessons? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Yes, adult comeback students are some of my favorites. We'll start by figuring out what you used to know and what you actually want to be able to play, then build from there. You'll be surprised how fast it comes back, and how much faster you can progress now compared to the first time around.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Do I need any background in music to start? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>No. I teach total beginners regularly. If you've never read a note of music or held a chord, that's completely fine. Most people start exactly there.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What's the best age to start a child on guitar? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Six is my minimum, and seven or eight is often a sweeter spot, old enough to focus through a 30-minute lesson and have hands big enough to fret a chord. Ukulele can work earlier (some kids do well at five). Every kid is different, feel free to ask before booking if you're unsure.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Do you teach adults? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Half my students are adults: beginners, comeback players, and lifelong hobbyists. The whole "kids only" thing about music lessons is a myth.</p></div>
      </div>

      </div>
    </div>
<div class="faq-cat">
      <div class="faq-cat-head">
        <span class="cat-num">// 02</span>
        <h2>Logistics &amp; Scheduling</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Where are lessons held? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>In-person lessons are held in the Suwanee, GA area, convenient to Sugar Hill, Buford, Duluth, John's Creek, Lawrenceville, and Cumming. Online lessons happen via video and work anywhere with decent internet.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What's the difference between in-person and online? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>The lesson itself is functionally identical: same plan, same materials, same teacher. In-person tends to work better for younger kids and absolute beginners (I can physically adjust hand position). Online works great for adults, busy schedules, families that travel, and anyone outside the local radius. Many students do a mix.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How long is each lesson? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Standard lessons are 30 minutes weekly. That's the sweet spot for most students, long enough to cover material, short enough to stay focused. Longer formats (45 or 60 minutes) are available on request, especially for advanced students who want to go deeper.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What if I need to miss a lesson? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>You get unlimited makeups as long as you give 24 hours notice. Things come up: kids get sick, work runs late, you have a tournament or a recital. The scheduling system makes rebooking straightforward from your phone.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What happens if I miss without giving notice? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Last-minute cancellations (under 24 hours) are typically counted as the lesson taking place, same as any private instructor. I'm as flexible as I can reasonably be, especially for genuine emergencies.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Can I take lessons at a different frequency than weekly? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Yes. Weekly is by far the most effective for steady progress, but I do bi-weekly arrangements and à la carte single lessons too. We can talk about what fits your life best.</p></div>
      </div>

      </div>
    </div>
<div class="faq-cat">
      <div class="faq-cat-head">
        <span class="cat-num">// 03</span>
        <h2>Pricing &amp; Payment</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How much do lessons cost? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <!-- TODO(jonathan): confirm à la carte price increase to $50 -->
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Weekly 30-minute lessons are $159/month (four lessons). Single à la carte lessons are $50 each. The free trial lesson is $0 and has no commitment afterward.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Are there registration fees, materials fees, or hidden costs? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>No. The monthly rate is the monthly rate. No registration fee, no materials fee, no recital fee. You'll need an instrument and a tuner; everything else is included.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How do I pay? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Tuition is billed monthly to a credit or debit card on file. Your card is charged on the same day each month, typically the date of your first lesson. À la carte lessons are paid at the time of booking.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Are there discounts? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Sibling discounts and multi-lesson bundle discounts are available, ask when you book. Active students also get 15% off accessories at Town Center Music in Suwanee.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Is the trial lesson really free? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Yes. No card needed, no obligation, no upsell pressure. It's 30 minutes for both of us to figure out if working together makes sense.</p></div>
      </div>

      </div>
    </div>
<div class="faq-cat">
      <div class="faq-cat-head">
        <span class="cat-num">// 04</span>
        <h2>What I Teach</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What styles do you specialize in? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>My deepest specialties are progressive rock, jazz fusion, funk, shred, and modern jam-band. But I teach across rock, blues, metal, classical fingerstyle basics, songwriting, theory, and ear training. The What I Teach page has a full breakdown.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Do you only teach electric guitar? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>No. Acoustic guitar, electric guitar, bass, and ukulele, same teacher, same studio, same rates.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Can you really teach total beginners and advanced players? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Yes. Beginners need clean technique, real songs, and ear training, and that's exactly the foundation I build. Advanced players come for specific things: alternate picking precision, jazz vocabulary, prog technique, getting unstuck creatively. The level changes; the habit of starting from what each student actually wants doesn't.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">I want to learn a really specific thing (like Phish-style improvisation, or Plini-style prog). Is that doable? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Yes, and frankly, those are some of my favorite asks. I play in a Phish tribute band; I've studied modern prog deeply. Specific goals make for great lessons. Mention it when you book.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Will I have to learn boring exercises and theory? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Some technique work and theory is unavoidable if you want to actually get good. But I keep it focused and tied directly to music you care about, not abstract drills. Nobody learns scales for fun, they learn scales because the solos they want to play are made of them.</p></div>
      </div>

      </div>
    </div>
<div class="faq-cat">
      <div class="faq-cat-head">
        <span class="cat-num">// 05</span>
        <h2>Equipment &amp; Practice</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Do I need my own guitar? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Yes, you'll need an instrument to practice on between lessons. Don't buy gear before our first lesson though; we'll talk through what makes sense at your budget. There's a workable beginner setup at every price point, and a lot of beginners get bad advice online.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What kind of guitar should I buy as a beginner? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Depends on what you want to play. For most kids: a 3/4-size acoustic or a small electric like a Squier Mini. For adults: a decent full-size acoustic ($150–$300) or an entry-level electric setup with a small amp ($250–$400). I'll send specific recommendations after we chat.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How much should I practice? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Fifteen to thirty minutes a day is the sweet spot. Consistency beats marathon sessions, a kid practicing 15 minutes daily will smoke a kid who does two hours on Sunday only.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What if I don't have time to practice some weeks? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>It happens, and we'll deal with it. Honestly, no practice means slower progress, math is math. But it's not a moral failing, and I'm not going to lecture you. We just adjust expectations and keep moving.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Can my child practice on a hand-me-down guitar that's falling apart? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Probably not, a guitar that's hard to play or impossible to tune will sabotage even the most motivated student. If you're not sure, bring it to the trial lesson and I'll tell you straight whether it's workable or whether you'd be better off spending $80 on a basic starter.</p></div>
      </div>

      </div>
    </div>
<div class="faq-cat">
      <div class="faq-cat-head">
        <span class="cat-num">// 06</span>
        <h2>About Me</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Are you a "real" musician or just a teacher? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Both. I've been gigging in the Atlanta area for over a decade. I'm the leader of Free Hat (three releases on Spotify), lead guitarist for Cadillac Rainbows (a Phish tribute), and a regular sit-in with the BadAsh Allstar Team. I play roughly every weekend. The About page has the full story.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How long have you been teaching? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Over five years of private guitar, bass, and ukulele instruction. I've worked with students of every age and level in that time.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Are you background-checked? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Yes. Any institutional teaching arrangement I work through requires it, and I'm happy to share documentation with parents on request.</p></div>
      </div>
<div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Can I come watch a Free Hat show? <span class="toggle">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Please do. Free Hat plays regularly around Atlanta, Pontoon Brewing, Smith's Olde Bar, Sweetwater Taproom, Aisle 5, MadLife Stage and others. Show calendar is on the Free Hat site (freehatmusic.com) and on Instagram @free_hat_music. Often the best way to know what your teacher actually sounds like.</p></div>
      </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="inline-cta" style="margin-top:60px">
      <div>
        <h3>Still Got Questions?</h3>
        <p>If you didn't find what you needed, the fastest way to get an answer is just to ask. The trial lesson is free either way.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/lessons#book" class="btn btn-primary" style="white-space:nowrap">Book a Free Trial <span class="arrow">→</span></a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
</BaseLayout>
